content:
When you create or update a dataset through your dataflow, recipe, or a CSV upload, for example, CRM Analytics replaces blank numeric values with the specified default value. When no default value is specified, CRM Analytics replaces blanks in numeric columns with 0 or null based on whether you enable null measure handling.

Null measure handling is enabled in orgs created after the Spring '17 release and can't be disabled. To enable this feature in other orgs, see Enable Null Measure Handling in Orgs Created Before Spring '17 .

CRM Analytics replaces blanks with:

0 when null measure handling is disabled and no default value is specified
null when null measure handling is enabled and no default value is specified

This behavior is important because CRM Analytics treats null and 0 differently. They aren't the same.

Null means that no value exists. 0 represents a value. Math operations performed on null results in null. For example, 10 + null = null

Aggregate functions—such as sum, average, count, min, and max—exclude null values from calculations.

Null measure handling allows the use of null values in these dataflow transformations.

CRM Analytics can append datasets with different measure columns. When appending datasets, CRM Analytics inserts nulls in rows without a match.

The defaultValue attribute for a computed column accepts a value of null.

When a value can't be calculated, such as when previous() or next() has no value, CRM Analytics uses the default specified.

CRM Analytics can update non-null values with nulls.

The delta transformation is not supported when null measure handling is enabled and dataflows containing delta transformations fail.
title: Handling Null Numeric Values in CRM Analytics
